-- ── Codecov (codecov.io) ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Codecov (codecov.io) is a code coverage reporting and analytics platform that ingests test coverage reports from CI pipelines and turns them into pull-request comments, dashboards, and trend graphs. Founded in 2015, it was acquired by Sentry in 2022 and then by Harness (from Sentry) in 2026. It integrates with GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket, and most CI providers to show teams exactly which lines and files lack test coverage.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Per-seat monthly or annual subscription with a free tier$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (Developer plan); paid plans start at $5 per user per month (Team plan)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2015, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Mid-size team operating as part of Harness; exact standalone headcount not publicly disclosed$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Francisco, California, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Codecov Review 2026: Pricing, Features and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$What Codecov does, how its coverage reporting works, 2026 pricing plans, integrations, pros and cons, and who it is really built for.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Codecov, accessible at codecov.io and about.codecov.io, is a code coverage reporting and analytics platform used by software teams to understand how much of their codebase is exercised by automated tests. Rather than running tests itself, Codecov ingests coverage reports, in formats like lcov, Cobertura XML, or JaCoCo, generated by a team's existing test runner during a CI pipeline run, then processes and visualizes that data. Its signature feature is posting automated coverage comments and status checks directly on GitHub, GitLab, and Bitbucket pull requests, showing reviewers exactly which new or changed lines are untested before code is merged, alongside file-by-file and project-wide coverage percentages, diff coverage, and historical trend graphs. Codecov was founded in 2015 by Jerrod Engelberg and Eli Hooten and grew into one of the most widely used coverage tools in the open-source and enterprise CI/CD ecosystem, integrating with virtually every major CI provider, including GitHub Actions, CircleCI, Travis CI, Jenkins, GitLab CI, and Azure Pipelines, via a lightweight uploader CLI or GitHub Action. In November 2022, application-monitoring company Sentry acquired Codecov to combine coverage insight with error monitoring and broader code-quality tooling. In June 2026, Codecov was acquired again, this time by Harness, a software delivery platform, which positioned the deal as embedding coverage intelligence directly into CI/CD release pipelines and software delivery governance. Throughout these ownership changes, Codecov has kept its own branding, product, and self-serve pricing page live at about.codecov.io. As of 2026, Codecov offers four tiers. The Developer plan is free, capped at one user (unlimited for public open-source repositories) with up to 250 private-repo uploads per month, and includes PR comments, status checks, API access, patch coverage, bundle-size analysis, failed-test reporting, and Slack notifications. The Team plan costs 5 US dollars per user per month, caps out at 10 users, raises the private-repo upload allowance to 2,500 per month, and adds project-level coverage, coverage flags, components, carryforward flags, flaky-test detection, and Sentry integration. The Pro plan costs 12 US dollars per user per month, removes the user cap and the upload cap entirely, and includes everything in Team. Enterprise pricing is custom and adds a dedicated cloud deployment option, faster processing, Okta single sign-on, dedicated IP allowlisting, a customer success manager, a solutions architect, dedicated onboarding, and legal support for regulated environments. Codecov's core value proposition is reducing the risk of merging undertested code by making coverage visible and actionable inside the existing pull-request workflow rather than requiring engineers to check a separate dashboard. Features like flags and components let large monorepos break coverage down by service or team ownership, while carryforward flags prevent coverage numbers from artificially dropping when only part of a test suite runs on a given commit. Bundle analysis, a newer addition, extends the same trend-tracking approach to JavaScript bundle size rather than just test coverage. Codecov is commonly compared to Coveralls, Code Climate, SonarQube and SonarCloud, and Codacy; its main differentiators are its long track record, broad CI and language support, and deep GitHub and GitLab pull-request integration. Typical users range from individual open-source maintainers on the free tier to enterprise engineering organizations that use coverage thresholds as a merge gate in regulated or high-reliability codebases.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '5d3384a3-5c53-49c6-8ec6-4333404223d5';

